data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3+ supports **strongly-typed `DynamicData`** using `Tuple`-based overloads, and MSTest v4 introduces `[TestDataSource]`. But the simplest modern improvement is using **`DynamicData` with typed tuples**:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

This requires **MSTest 3.8+** which added `IEnumerable<ValueTuple>` support for `[DynamicData]`. Benefits:

- Compile-time type safety (no casts from `object[]`)
- Named tuple members for readability
- Refactoring-friendly — renaming/retyping breaks the build instead of failing at runtime

If you're on **MSTest 4+**, you can also use the new `[TestDataSource<T1, T2>]` attribute for even tighter coupling between data and parameters.
